[FULL TEXT ANALYSIS BELOW]
Glucagon-Like Peptide-1 Receptor Signaling in the Ventral
Tegmental Area Reduces Alcohol Self-Administration in
Male Rats
Tiarani N. Dixon, Gavan P. McNally, and Zhi Yi Ong
Background: The misuse and abuse of alcohol is a major public health issue. However, available
treatments are limited with variable eﬃcacy. Recently, preclinical studies show that glucagon-like-pep-
tide-1 (GLP-1) and its analogue Exendin-4 (Ex4) potently reduce a range of alcohol intake behaviors,
thus highlighting its potential as a treatment for alcohol use disorders. However, the neural mechanisms
and sites of action mediating the eﬀects of Ex4 on alcohol intake behaviors remain to be characterized.
This study examined the ventral tegmental area (VTA) as a site of action for the eﬀects of GLP-1 on
alcohol intake.
Methods: Male Long-Evans rats were given intermittent access to 20% alcohol and trained to nose
poke for 20% alcohol. Rats received intra-VTA injections of Ex4 (vehicle, 0.01, 0.05 lg), and the eﬀects
of VTA Ex4 on alcohol self-administration, motivation, and relapse were assessed.
Results: When compared to vehicle treatment, intra-VTA Ex4 (0.01, 0.05 lg) delivery signiﬁcantly
reduced alcohol self-administration, an eﬀect that was particularly prominent in high alcohol drinkers.
However, VTA Ex4 did not reduce reacquisition of alcohol self-administration after extinction nor the
motivation to obtain alcohol. Importantly, the lower dose of Ex4 (0.01 lg) used had no eﬀect on food
intake or locomotor activity, suggesting that the reduction in alcohol self-administration observed was
not secondary to caloric intake or motor deﬁcits.
Conclusions: Together, these ﬁndings provide support for the VTA as a key site of action for GLP-1
on alcohol self-administration but not the reacquisition of alcohol self-administration or motivation to
work for alcohol.
Key Words: Glucagon-Like Peptide-1, Ventral Tegmental Area, Alcohol Self-Administration,
Motivation, Relapse.
A
LCOHOL USE DISORDER (AUD) is a leading risk
factor for disability, morbidity, and mortality. In 2016,
an estimated 1 in 20 deaths was caused by alcohol worldwide
(World Health Organization, 2018). Unlike other illicit sub-
stances of abuse, alcohol is both legal and widely accepted,
making it exceptionally prevalent within our society. As a
result, its misuse is particularly diﬃcult to identify, control,
and treat, and it remains one of our biggest public health
issues to date. The only medications approved by the Food
and Drug Administration are acamprosate, disulﬁram, and
naltrexone. The limited eﬃcacy of current pharmacotherapy
for the treatment of AUD (Swift & Aston, 2015) calls for the
development and identiﬁcation of better AUD pharma-
cotherapies.
Glucagon-like-peptide-1 (GLP-1), a peptide well known
for its eﬀects on glycemic and energy balance control (Hayes,
2012; Kanoski et al., 2016), has received increasing attention
as a potential treatment for AUD (Jerlhag, 2020; Reddy
et al., 2014). Preclinical studies show that systemic delivery
of long acting GLP-1 analogues (e.g., liraglutide and Exen-
din-4 [Ex4]) reduces alcohol consumption, alcohol seeking,
and motivated behaviors in mice, rats, alcohol-preferring
rats, and a mouse model of alcohol dependence (Egecioglu
et al., 2013c; Shirazi et al., 2013; Suchankova et al., 2015;
Vallof et al., 2016) and prevents tolerance to the antianxiety
eﬀect of alcohol and withdrawal-induced anxiety (Sharma
et al., 2015). These ﬁndings in rodent models were recently
replicated in alcohol-preferring vervet monkeys (Thomsen
et al., 2019), thus demonstrating that the eﬀects of GLP-1
and alcohol intake are not limited to rodents and have the
potential to be translated to a clinical setting. Indeed, a clini-
cal trial is currently underway to elucidate the eﬃcacy of
GLP-1 as a treatment for AUD (Antonsen et al., 2018).
While the role of GLP-1 in reducing alcohol intake behaviors
is promising, the mechanisms and sites of action through
which GLP-1 analogues reduce alcohol intake behaviors
remain to be characterized.
The eﬀects of GLP-1 on alcohol-taking behaviors are
thought to be mediated via central sites as mice with a brain-
speciﬁc genetic knockout of GLP-1 receptor (GLP-1R) fail
to respond to the inhibitory eﬀects of systemic GLP-1 on
