alcohol intake (Sirohi et al., 2016). Interestingly, brain
GLP-1R deﬁciency only partially blocked the eﬀects of
GLP-1 on hedonic feeding behavior measured with chow
and high-fat diet intake, suggesting a speciﬁcity of brain
GLP-1R to substance of abuse (Sirohi et al., 2016). Stud-
ies also show that GLP-1 analogues reduce alcohol intake
in part by reducing alcohol-induced accumbal DA release
(Egecioglu et al., 2013c; Vallof et al., 2016), suggesting
that GLP-1 could be acting via the mesolimbic reward
system.
Indeed,
GLP-1R
is
expressed
in
mesolimbic
reward areas including the ventral tegmental area (VTA;
Cork et al., 2015; Merchenthaler et al., 1999). Studies
probing the eﬀects of GLP-1 in the VTA revealed that
GLP-1R signaling in the VTA reduces alcohol intake and
alcohol-induced locomotor activity (Shirazi et al., 2013;
Vallof et al., 2019a). However, alcohol intake was limited
to home cage drinking and other aspects of AUD that
are of clinical relevance, including alcohol self-administra-
tion, relapse to alcohol seeking, and the increased motiva-
tion to obtain alcohol, were not examined. In order to
determine the eﬃcacy of GLP-1 analogues as potential
AUD treatments, it is important to assess whether VTA
GLP-1R signaling also reduces these relevant alcohol
intake behaviors.
The current study therefore aimed to examine the eﬀects
of VTA GLP-1R signaling on a range of clinically relevant
alcohol intake behaviors. Speciﬁcally, a series of behavioral
experiments were conducted to examine whether the GLP-1
analogue Ex4 delivered to the VTA reduces operant alcohol
self-administration, reacquisition of alcohol seeking, and
motivation to work for alcohol under a progressive ratio
(PR) schedule of reinforcement.
MATERIALS AND METHODS
Animals
Male Long-Evans rats (Randwick, Sydney; n = 22) 7 to 8 weeks
old upon arrival were housed in groups of 3 and 4 in ventilated
racks within a climate-controlled, 12-hour light/dark cycle colony
room (Lights on 7:00 AM). Food (Gordon’s Specialty Stock Feeds)
and water were available ad libitum. All experiments were con-
ducted during the light cycle, and procedures were approved by The
University of New South Wales Animal Care and Ethics Commit-
tee.
Surgery
Rats were anesthetized with an intraperitoneal injection of a mix-
ture of 1.3 ml/kg ketamine (Ketamil 100 mg/ml, Ilium) and 0.3 ml/
kg xylazine (Xylazil 20 mg/ml, Ilium). Rats were implanted with a
bilateral guide cannula (1.5 mm c-c; Plastics One Inc, Roanoke,
VA, USA) targeting the VTA (AP 5.8 mm, ML 0.0 mm, DV
7.2 mm; Paxinos & Watson, 2007). Guide cannula was secured by
jewelers screws and dental cement. Following surgery, rats received
subcutaneous injections of analgesic carprofen (Rimadyl 50 mg/ml,
Zoetis) and antibiotics procaine penicillin (Benicillin, Ilium) and
cephazolin sodium (Hospira). A dummy cannula was inserted, and
a metal dust cap screwed to the top of the guide cannula. Rats were
allowed 1 week to recover from surgery during which time they
were monitored and weighed daily.
Drugs
For all experiments, a 10% or 20% (vol/vol) alcohol solution
diluted from ethyl alcohol 80% (vol/vol) with tap water was used.
For all tests, GLP-1R agonist Ex4 (Bachem) and its vehicle (0.9%
sodium chloride) were used. Ex4 was diluted with saline (0.9%
sodium chloride) to obtain a ﬁnal dose of 0.01 lg/100 nl or 0.05 lg/
100 nl. Doses of Ex4 were chosen based on previous literature to be
eﬀective at reducing drug seeking (Hernandez et al., 2018) with the
higher dose (0.05 lg/100 nl), but not the lower dose (0.01 lg/
100 nl), known to also reduce food intake (Alhadeﬀet al., 2012;
Mietlicki-Baase et al., 2013). Thirty minutes prior to testing, unilat-
eral VTA infusions of 100 nl Ex4 or vehicle were delivered via an
infusion pump at a rate of 1 ll/min and injector tips were left in
place for a further 30 seconds for complete drug diﬀusion. A unilat-
eral infusion tip extending 1.5 mm from the guide cannula was used.
Unilateral infusions were performed using a bilateral cannula such
that Experiments 1 and 2 received infusions on 1 side, while Experi-
ments 3 and 4 received infusions on the other side (na€ıve). Infusions
were performed this way to enable the assessment of VTA Ex4 on
alcohol intake behaviors in the same animal without compromising
tissue integrity. All experiments were conducted using a within-sub-
jects design such that each rat served as its own control. Treatment
and infusion sides were also counterbalanced. Figure 1A shows the
experimental timeline.
Intermittent Access 20% Alcohol 2-Bottle-Choice Drinking
Procedure
Rats were trained to voluntarily and reliably consume alcohol via
the intermittent access 2-bottle-choice drinking procedure. This is a
well-established paradigm shown to induce high levels of alcohol
consumption and produce pharmacologically relevant blood alco-
hol concentrations in Long-Evans rats, comparable to that of selec-
tively bred alcohol-preferring (P) rats (Carnicella et al., 2014; Simms
et al., 2008). In the current study, rats were given intermittent access
to alcohol (Monday, Wednesday, Friday) for 4 weeks. During alco-
hol access periods, rats had free access to 1 bottle of alcohol solution
and 1 bottle of water in their home cages. A 10% alcohol solution
was used for the ﬁrst 2 weeks, and a 20% alcohol solution was used
for the following 2 weeks. In between access periods, both bottles
contained water. To account for side preferences, bottles were alter-
nated at each alcohol access period. Food was available ad libitum.
Rats were group housed to reduce the eﬀects of chronic social isola-
tion stress, so the volume of alcohol consumed during the intermit-
tent access period was averaged across rats in each cage and
subsequently divided by their individual body weights to determine
the amount of alcohol consumed within a 24-hour period (g/kg
alcohol in 24 hour). During the last week of the 20% alcohol inter-
mittent access period, rats consumed an average of 4.64  0.2 g/
kg/24 h alcohol, which is similar to the levels considered as high
alcohol consumption (5 to 10 g/kg/24 h) and twice the normal level
of alcohol intake in a Long-Evans rat (2 to 2.5 g/kg/24 h; Leeman
et al., 2010).
Apparatus for Operant Responding for Alcohol
To examine the role of GLP-1R signaling in the VTA on alcohol
intake behaviors, rats underwent 3 behavioral paradigms that
involved
operant
responding
for
alcohol:
Self-administration
(Experiment 1), Reacquisition (Experiment 2), and PR (Experiment
3). All tests were conducted in standard Med Associates operant
chambers (Med Associates, St Albans, VT) housed in sound attenu-
ating cubicles. Each chamber consisted of a perspex ceiling, perspex
front and back walls, stainless steel side walls, and steel-grid ﬂoor-
ing. There were 2 nose poke ports positioned on the right wall of
each chamber and a stimulus light directly above each port.
VTA GLP-1 AND ALCOHOL SELF-ADMINISTRATION
2119
Positioned in the middle of the same wall, in between both ports,
was a small magazine dish where 20% alcohol was delivered via a
syringe connected to an external pump.
Experiment 1: Eﬀects of VTA Ex4 on Alcohol Self-Administration
We used the operant alcohol self-administration model where the
delivery of alcohol was contingent upon the operant response. This
self-administration behavior is positively reinforced by the reward-
ing properties of alcohol, thus allowing us to examine alcohol
intake, as consumed for its rewarding properties. Rats were trained
to nose poke (operant response) for 20% alcohol solution using a
ﬁxed ratio 1 (FR1) schedule of reinforcement such that each nose
poke in the active port (active nose poke) triggered the delivery of
1 9 200 ll 20% alcohol solution. Nose pokes in the inactive port
(inactive nose poke) had no programmed consequences. Each active
nose poke and alcohol delivery were accompanied by a discrete light
and tone compound cue (78 dB, 2,900 Hz; white stimulus light
above the active hole) followed by an 8-second time-out period.
Training sessions were 30 minutes daily for 4 weeks. During test
days, rats received intra-VTA injections of vehicle (0 lg) or Ex4
(0.01, 0.05 lg) in a counterbalanced order with 2 days in between
each treatment to prevent any drug carry over eﬀects. Thirty min-
utes after injections, rats were placed in the operant chambers and
were allowed to self-administer alcohol under FR1. The number of
active and inactive nose pokes, magazine entries, and total number
of alcohol deliveries was recorded using MED-PC IV software
(Med Associates). The number of active nose pokes during the time-
out period was also obtained by subtracting the total number of
active nose pokes to the number of reinforced active nose pokes.
In addition to operant responses, food intake was also recorded
before each test session and 24 hours after to determine whether the
Ex4 doses used have any eﬀects on food intake. Given that rats were
group housed, all rats in the same cage received the same treatment
during each test day and food intake was measured per cage.
Experiment 2: Eﬀects of VTA Ex4 on Reacquisition of Alcohol
Self-Administration
Reacquisition is a well-established animal model of relapse where
following a period of extinction, the operant behavior (e.g., nose
poke) is again paired with alcohol availability, causing a rapid recur-
rence of alcohol self-administration (Willcocks and McNally, 2011)
and transient spike in alcohol consumption, also known as the alco-
hol deprivation eﬀect (McKinzie et al., 1998). Following FR1 alco-
hol self-administration, rats underwent at least 5 extinction sessions
to extinguish operant responses. Extinction was achieved when
there were <10 active nose pokes in 2 consecutive sessions. Reacqui-
sition test was performed under the same FR1 instrumental contin-
gency, used in self-administration training. There were 2 9 30-
minutes reacquisition test sessions where rats received intra-VTA
injections of either vehicle or Ex4 (0.01 lg) in a counterbalanced
order. Test sessions were separated by 5 extinction sessions or when
extinction criteria were achieved (<10 active nose pokes in 2
Fig. 1. (A) Experimental timeline and (B) VTA cannula placements. Black circles indicate placements for HAD, and brown circles indicate place-
ments for LAD.
2120
DIXON ET AL.
consecutive sessions) to ensure responses were extinguished before
the following test and to prevent any drug carry over eﬀects. The
number of active and inactive nose pokes, magazine entries, and
total number of alcohol deliveries was recorded.
Experiment 3: Eﬀects of VTA Ex4 on the Motivation to Work for
Alcohol
We used a PR schedule of reinforcement such that the number of
active nose pokes required to acquire alcohol increases exponen-
tially, thus allowing us to examine the motivation to work for and
consume alcohol. Rats were ﬁrst retrained to self-administer alcohol
under FR1 for 2 days followed by FR3 (3 nose pokes in the active
port trigger 1 delivery of alcohol) for an additional 3 days. Rats
were then put on a PR schedule of reinforcement based on the fol-
lowing equation: F(i) = 5e0.2i  5 (Richardson and Roberts, 1996),
whereby a single delivery of 200 ll 20% alcohol solution was deliv-
ered each time the required response ratio was achieved. PR training
sessions were 1 hour each day and ran for 9 days until average
intersession variability for alcohol deliveries was <15%. During test
days, rats received intra-VTA injections of either vehicle or Ex4
(0.01 lg) using a within-subjects, counterbalanced design. Each
treatment was separated by 3 days of PR training to reestablish PR
responding and to prevent any drug carry over eﬀects. The number
of active and inactive nose pokes, magazine entries, and total num-
ber of alcohol deliveries was recorded.
Experiment 4: Eﬀects of VTA Ex4 on Locomotor Activity
To ensure the eﬀects observed in the current study were not due
to any impairments in motor behavior, we examined whether deliv-
ery of Ex4 to the VTA aﬀected locomotor activity. A subset of rats
(n = 12) was ﬁrst habituated to a 43 cm 9 43 cm 9 30 cm open-
ﬁeld arena (Med Associates) for 1 hour each day for 2 days prior to
test sessions. During test days, rats received intra-VTA injections of
either vehicle or Ex4 (0.01 lg). Thirty minutes after injections, they
were placed in the open-ﬁeld arena and rat movement was recorded
by breaks in infrared beams located at the base of each arena. Loco-
motor activity was deﬁned as the accumulated number of new infra-
red beams interrupted during a 60-minute period. Injections were
separated by 3 days to prevent any drug carry over eﬀects.
Cannula Placement Veriﬁcation
Upon completion of all tests, rats were sacriﬁced with an
intraperitoneal injection of 0.5 ml of 1:1 mixture of lethabarb and
marcaine. Post mortem, rats received intra-VTA injections of
0.2 ml Pontamine Sky Blue. Rats were then perfused with 4%
paraformaldehyde, and brains removed. Brains were sectioned
using a cryostat. 35-lm sections of the VTA were collected and
mounted onto slides. Sections were visualized under a light micro-
scope for blue ink and local tissue damage. VTA cannula placement
was histologically veriﬁed according to The Rat Brain in Stereotaxic
Coordinates (Paxinos & Watson, 2007; Fig. 1B). Rats with incor-
rect cannula placement were excluded from analysis.
Statistical Analysis
Data were reported as mean  SEM and analyzed using IBM
SPSS Statistics 26 (IBM, Armonk, NY, USA). The number of
active and inactive nose pokes, magazine entries, total number of
alcohol deliveries, and g/kg alcohol were the primary dependent
variables used to analyze alcohol intake behaviors. For g/kg alcohol
data, 1 rat was excluded as body weight was not recorded. Data for
Experiment 1 were evaluated using a repeated measures analysis of
variation (ANOVA). As individual variation in self-administration
behavior was observed in Experiment 1, a median split was used to
assign the cohort into high alcohol drinkers (HAD) and low alcohol
drinkers (LAD), and data were analyzed using a mixed model
ANOVA. For Experiments 2 and 3, all data were analyzed using
paired t tests with the exception of nose poke data which were ana-
lyzed using a repeated measures 2-way ANOVA. Data from Experi-
ment 4 were analyzed using repeated measures ANOVA. Given that
cannula placements ranged from anterior to posterior VTA, a fur-
ther analysis on anterior versus posterior VTA was performed for
Experiments 1 to 3 using a mixed model ANOVA to examine any
VTA regional diﬀerences on the eﬀects of Ex4 on alcohol intake
behaviors. When a signiﬁcant interaction or main eﬀect was
observed, pairwise comparisons with Bonferroni correction were
performed to compare diﬀerences between treatments. The type 1
error rate of 0.05 was used to determine statistical signiﬁcance.
RESULTS
Experiment 1: VTA Ex4 Reduced FR1 Alcohol Self-
Administration
Figure 2A shows the mean  SEM nose pokes during test
for self-administration. Repeated measures 2-way ANOVA
revealed a main eﬀect of nose pokes, F(1, 21) = 101.572,
p < 0.01, where rats made signiﬁcantly more active nose
pokes compared to inactive nose pokes. There was also a
main eﬀect of treatment, F(2, 42) = 5.535, p < 0.01, and a
nose
