and subsequent pairwise analysis with Bonferroni correction
showed that 0.01 and 0.05 lg Ex4 signiﬁcantly reduced
active nose pokes for 20% alcohol when compared to vehicle
treatment (p < 0.05), with no diﬀerence between 0.01 and
0.05 lg Ex4 (p > 0.05). There was no eﬀect of treatment on
inactive nose pokes, F(2, 42) = 0.301, p > 0.05 (Fig. 2A).
We also measured the number of nonreinforced active
nose pokes made during the 8-second time-out period in
between alcohol delivery. We ﬁrst showed that the number
of reinforced active nose pokes was signiﬁcantly higher than
nonreinforced time-out nose pokes regardless of whether rats
