When data were analyzed for LAD, there was a main
eﬀect of nose pokes, F(1, 9) = 64.867, p < 0.01, with greater
active nose pokes than inactive nose pokes, but no eﬀect of
treatment, F(2, 18) = 0.706, p > 0.05, or treatment 9 nose
pokes interaction, F(2, 18) = 0.029, p > 0.05 (Fig. 3D).
There was also no main eﬀect of treatment on deliveries, F(2,
18) = 0.446, p > 0.05 (Fig. 3E) or magazine entries, F(2,
18) = 0.608, p > 0.05 (Fig. 3F) in LAD. For g/kg alcohol
analysis, there was no main eﬀect on treatment, F(2,
16) = 0.79, p > 0.05 (vehicle: 0.54  0.09g/kg, 0.01 lg Ex4:
0.70  0.13g/kg, 0.05 lg Ex4: 0.64  0.08g/kg).
Together, these results show that although both doses of
Ex4 signiﬁcantly reduced 20% alcohol self-administration
behavior when compared to vehicle, this eﬀect was promi-
nent in HAD.
We also examined the eﬀects of intra-VTA Ex4 delivery
on chow intake in all rats. Repeated measures ANOVA
showed a main eﬀect of treatment on food intake, F(2,
14) = 18.636, p < 0.01 (Fig. 2D). Pairwise comparisons with
Bonferroni correction revealed that 0.05 lg Ex4 signiﬁcantly
reduced food intake when compared to vehicle (p < 0.01)
and when compared to 0.01 lg (p < 0.01). There was no dif-
ference in chow intake between vehicle and 0.01 lg Ex4
(p > 0.05). Given that there was no diﬀerence in operant
responding between 0.01 and 0.05 lg Ex4 and that 0.05 lg
Ex4, but not 0.01 lg Ex4 reduced food intake, subsequent
experiments only used 0.01 lg Ex4.
Experiment 2: VTA Ex4 Had no Eﬀect on Reacquisition of
Alcohol Seeking
To ensure that rats reacquired alcohol self-administration
behavior, we compared responding during extinction (aver-
age of the last 3 days of extinction) and reacquisition when
rats were injected with vehicle to the VTA. Paired t tests
revealed a signiﬁcant higher active nose poke response in
vehicle-treated rats during reacquisition than during extinc-
tion (t(21) = 5.032, p < 0.01), indicating that rats reacquired
alcohol self-administration behavior. When the eﬀects of
VTA Ex4 on reacquisition of alcohol seeking were examined,
there was a main eﬀect on nose pokes, F(1, 21) = 58.185,
p < 0.01, but no eﬀect on treatment, F(1, 21) = 0.075,
p > 0.05,
or
nose
pokes 9 treatment
interaction,
F(1,
21) = 0.257, p > 0.05, during reacquisition (Fig. 4A). There
was also no eﬀect of Ex4 treatment on alcohol deliveries
(t(21) = 0.773, p > 0.05) or magazine entries (t(21) = 0.191,
p > 0.05) during reacquisition (Fig. 4B,C). When analyzed
for g/kg alcohol, there were no diﬀerences between groups
(t(21) = 0.651, p > 0.05; vehicle: 0.96  0.17g/kg, 0.01 lg
Ex4: 1.06  0.13g/kg).Thus, these results indicate that VTA
Ex4 had no eﬀect on reacquisition of alcohol self-administra-
tion.
Experiment 3: VTA Ex4 Had no Eﬀect on the Motivation to
Work for Alcohol
For PR, repeated measures 2-way ANOVA revealed a
main eﬀect of nose pokes, F(1, 21) = 21.137, p < 0.01, but
no main eﬀect of treatment, F(1, 21) = 2.357, p > 0.05) or
nose
pokes 9 treatment
interaction,
F(1,
21) = 1.945,
p > 0.05 (Fig. 4D). Paired t tests also showed no signiﬁcant
diﬀerence in the number of alcohol deliveries (t(21) = 0.666,
p > 0.05) or magazine entries (t(21) = 0.380, p > 0.05) when
treated with Ex4 compared to vehicle (Fig. 4E,F). Together,
these results indicate that VTA Ex4 had no eﬀect on the
motivation to obtain alcohol.
Experiment 4: VTA Ex4 Had no Eﬀect on Locomotor
Activity
To ensure that the dose of Ex4 used in the experiments
(0.01 lg) did not cause any impairments in motor behavior,
we measured locomotor activity when rats were injected with
Ex4 or vehicle to the VTA. A repeated measures 2-way
ANOVA revealed a signiﬁcant main eﬀect of time, F(5,
50) = 33.658, p < 0.01, as naturally, and rats were more
active during the ﬁrst 10 minutes. However, there was no
main eﬀect of treatment, F(1, 10) = 1.241, p > 0.05, nor
time 9 treatment interaction, F(5, 50) = 1.455, p > 0.05
(Fig. 4G). These results suggest that Ex4 at a dose of 0.01 lg
did not impair locomotor activity.
VTA Regional Diﬀerences Do Not Contribute to the Eﬀects of
Ex4 on Alcohol Intake Behaviors
Cannula placements in this study were distributed across
the rostral–caudal axis of the VTA (Fig. 1). Previous studies
show that the eﬀects of Ex4 on alcohol intake can be depen-
dent upon VTA region such that Ex4 delivered to posterior
VTA reduces home cage alcohol intake but not when
VTA GLP-1 AND ALCOHOL SELF-ADMINISTRATION
2123
delivered to anterior VTA (Vallof et al., 2019a). Thus, we
performed additional analysis to determine whether there are
regional diﬀerences for Ex4-induced suppression of alcohol
intake. Cannula placements anterior to Bregma 5.4 mm
were classiﬁed as anterior VTA, while those at and posterior
to Bregma 5.4 mm were classiﬁed as posterior VTA. Here,
we ﬁrst showed that cannula placements for HAD and LAD
were equally distributed across the rostral–caudal axis of the
VTA, so any diﬀerences in responses between VTA regions
were not due to individual diﬀerences in alcohol consump-
tion. We performed a mixed model ANOVA such that the
between-subject factor is VTA region and within-subjects
factors are treatment and nose pokes. For alcohol self-ad-
ministration, there was a main eﬀect of nose pokes, F(1,
20) = 138.104, p < 0.01, and treatment 9 nose pokes inter-
action, F(2, 40) = 3.464, p < 0.05, but no interactions for
nose pokes 9 VTA region, F(1, 20) = 0.312, p > 0.05, treat-
ment 9 VTA
region,
F(2,
19) = 0.685,
p > 0.05,
nose
pokes 9 treatment 9 VTA
region,
F(2,
19) = 1.978,
p > 0.05, or deliveries 9 VTA region, F(2, 19) = 1.606,
p > 0.05. Similarly, we did not observe any regional
diﬀerences when the eﬀects of Ex4 on reacquisition, nose
pokes 9 treatment 9 VTA
region:
F(1,
20) = 0.543,
p > 0.05, or PR, nose pokes 9 treatment 9 VTA region: F
(1, 20) = 0.00, p > 0.05) were assessed (Table 1). Thus, we
did not observe any VTA regional diﬀerences on the eﬀects
of Ex4 on alcohol intake behaviors.
DISCUSSION
GLP-1, a peptide well-characterized for its roles in glyce-
mic and energy balance control (Hayes, 2012; Kanoski et al.,
2016), has recently received increasing attention for its con-
tributions to reducing alcohol intake behaviors (Jerlhag,
2020; Reddy et al., 2014). Furthermore, clinical trials are cur-
rently underway examining the eﬃcacy of GLP-1 analogues
in patients with AUD (Antonsen et al., 2018). However, the
underlying mechanisms and sites of action through which
GLP-1 reduces alcohol intake are unclear. Here, we showed
that intra-VTA delivery of the GLP-1 analogue, Ex4,
reduced established alcohol self-administration, especially in
HAD, but did not have any eﬀects on reacquisition of
Fig. 3. Effects of intra-VTA delivery of vehicle, 0.01 and 0.05 lg Ex4 on FR1 alcohol self-administration in Long-Evans HAD and LAD. In HAD, 0.01
and 0.05 lg Ex4 signiﬁcantly reduced (A) active nose pokes, but not inactive nose pokes, (B) alcohol deliveries when compared to vehicle. (C) 0.01 lg
Ex4 also reduced magazine entries. In LAD, 0.01 and 0.05 lg Ex4 had no effect on (D) nose pokes, (E) alcohol deliveries, (F) magazine entries. Each line
indicates responses from a single animal following treatment. *p < 0.05, **p < 0.01 compared to vehicle treatment.
2124
DIXON ET AL.
alcohol self-administration or the motivation to work for
alcohol. Importantly, the eﬀects of VTA GLP-1R signaling
on alcohol self-administration, when assessed using 0.01 lg
Ex4, were independent of any eﬀects on food intake or loco-
motor activity. Together, these ﬁndings provide evidence for
the VTA as a site of action for the inhibitory eﬀects of GLP-
1 on alcohol self-administration and suggest that any eﬀects
of GLP-1 on alcohol relapse and motivation for alcohol, at
least when assessed via reacquisition and PR respectively, are
achieved via actions elsewhere.
Accumulating evidence shows that GLP-1 reduces alcohol
intake
behaviors
including
alcohol
self-administration,
Fig. 4. Effects of intra-VTA delivery of vehicle, 0.01 lg Ex4 on alcohol relapse, motivation, and locomotor activity. There was no effect of Ex4 on (A)
reacquisition of alcohol self-administration, (B) motivation to work for alcohol when tested under a PR paradigm, or (C) locomotor activity.
VTA GLP-1 AND ALCOHOL SELF-ADMINISTRATION
2125
motivation, and relapse (Bornebusch et al., 2019; Egecioglu
et al., 2013c; Sorensen et al., 2016; Thomsen et al., 2017).
While the eﬀects of GLP-1 are thought to be centrally medi-
ated (Sirohi et al., 2016), the speciﬁc sites of action were
unclear. Several studies implicate the VTA as a nuclear sub-
strate responsible for the eﬀects of GLP-1 on home cage
alcohol intake (Shirazi et al., 2013) and alcohol-induced
locomotor activity (Vallof et al., 2019a). However, whether
GLP-1R signaling in the VTA also reduces other aspects of
alcohol intake behaviors was unknown. We therefore investi-
gated the eﬀects of VTA GLP-1R signaling on alcohol self-
administration, reacquisition of alcohol self-administration,
and the motivation to work for alcohol. We showed that
GLP-1 analogue Ex4 when delivered to the VTA reduced
alcohol self-administration, with signiﬁcant reductions in
active nose pokes and alcohol deliveries. Our data are consis-
tent with previous work showing that systemic GLP-1
reduces alcohol self-administration, but importantly, our
ﬁnding adds to the existing literature by identifying the VTA
as a site of action for GLP-1’s eﬀect on alcohol self-adminis-
tration. Given that rodents, like humans, exhibit individual
variation in alcohol intake (Spoelder et al., 2015), we per-
formed additional analysis to examine whether the eﬀects of
VTA Ex4 were speciﬁc to HAD, LAD, or both. We found
that VTA Ex4 signiﬁcantly reduced alcohol self-administra-
tion in HAD but not LAD. This is in line with previous stud-
ies using Wistar rats where systemic administration of Ex4
reduces home cage alcohol intake only in HAD but not in
LAD (Shirazi et al., 2013). Thus, Ex4-induced reductions in
alcohol self-administration are observed primarily in those
with high levels of alcohol consumption. This is of clinical
interest. Some pharmacotherapies (e.g., nalmefene) are avail-
able for, and are modestly eﬃcacious in, AUD individuals
with a high drinking risk level (e.g., alcohol >60 g/d for men
and >40 g/d for women) and who are not able to reduce their
alcohol consumption after assessment and brief intervention
(Laramee et al., 2014, van den Brink et al., 2013). These same
individuals may stand to beneﬁt from Ex4.
Given that alcohol contains calories and that VTA GLP-
1R signaling was previously shown to reduce food intake
and reward (Alhadeﬀet al., 2012; Dickson et al., 2012;
Mietlicki-Baase et al., 2013), we wanted to conﬁrm that the
eﬀects observed with alcohol self-administration were inde-
pendent of any eﬀects on food intake. Consistent with pre-
vious studies, we showed that 0.05 lg Ex4, but not the
0.01 lg Ex4, signiﬁcantly reduced food intake, suggesting
that the eﬀects of 0.01 lg Ex4 on alcohol intake were not
due to an overall reduction in caloric intake. This ﬁnding
that low Ex4 dose reduces responding for alcohol without
eﬀects on food has also been shown in other studies on
drugs of abuse. For example, VTA Ex4 suppresses cocaine
self-administration and cocaine-seeking, but has no eﬀect
on sucrose self-administration or seeking behavior (Her-
nandez et al., 2018; Schmidt et al., 2016). Furthermore, we
also showed that 0.01 lg Ex4 did not reduce locomotor
activity thus indicating that the inhibitory eﬀects of VTA
Ex4 on alcohol self-administration behavior were not due
to a general impairment in motility. Collectively, these ﬁnd-
ings show that VTA GLP-1R signaling reduces alcohol
intake by attenuating the reinforcing properties of alcohol,
independent of any eﬀects on food intake or locomotor
activity.
We also examined the eﬀects of VTA GLP-1R signaling
on alcohol relapse. There are several animal models of
relapse, including extinction-based models such as reinstate-
ment and reacquisition (Venniro et al., 2016). In this study,
we used the reacquisition model where operant responding
for alcohol is reinforced with the delivery of alcohol after a
period of extinction/abstinence. Thus, the subsequent pairing
of operant behavior with alcohol delivery causes reacquisi-
tion of the previously extinguished operant response, result-
ing in a surge in alcohol consumption. This behavior may
also assess aspects of the alcohol deprivation eﬀect, where
alcohol deprivation results in signiﬁcant increases in alcohol
consumption when given the opportunity to consume
(McKinzie et al., 1998). We chose to examine reacquisition
of alcohol seeking as previous studies showed that systemic
administration of GLP-1 analogues, liraglutide and Ex4,
reduces alcohol deprivation eﬀect (Thomsen et al., 2017; Val-
lof et al., 2016). In contrast to these studies, we did not
observe any eﬀects on reacquisition of alcohol self-adminis-
tration after VTA delivery of Ex4. It is possible that the
