DIXON ET AL.
eﬀects of the long acting GLP-1 analogues on alcohol relapse
and seeking behaviors may be achieved via other peripheral
or central sites. For example, the inhibitory eﬀects of Ex4 on
alcohol intake are also observed when Ex4 is delivered to
brain regions implicated in addiction and reward including
the nucleus accumbens shell (Abtahi et al., 2018; Vallof et al.,
2019a), lateral dorsal tegmental area (Vallof et al., 2019a),
and the nucleus of the solitary tract (Vallof et al., 2019b).
Whether these brain regions mediate the eﬀects of Ex4 on
reacquisition of alcohol self-administration remains to be
determined.
Previous studies show that systemic Ex4 also reduces PR
responding for alcohol (Egecioglu et al., 2013c; Shirazi et al.,
2013) but the site of action was not examined. Our ﬁndings
indicate that intra-VTA Ex4 had no eﬀect on the motivation
to obtain alcohol in a PR schedule of reinforcement and sug-
gests that GLP-1R activation in the VTA is not suﬃcient to
reduce the motivation to work for alcohol. This ﬁnding is
surprising given that the VTA dopamine neurons are impli-
cated in motivation and that VTA GLP-1R signaling reduces
motivation to work for cocaine (Schmidt et al., 2016) and
sucrose (Dickson et al., 2012). These eﬀects of GLP-1R sig-
naling in the VTA are thought to be mediated via VTA
dopamine neurons because Ex4 binds to VTA dopamine
neurons (Hernandez et al., 2018) and reduces the excitatory
synaptic potential of VTA dopamine neurons that project to
the nucleus accumbens shell (Wang et al., 2015). One study,
however, reported that Ex4 stimulates VTA dopamine neu-
rons and increases VTA tyrosine hydroxylase protein levels
(Mietlicki-Baase et al., 2013) but this could be due to the tar-
geting of more caudal parts of the VTA. Furthermore, cen-
tral GLP-1R signaling attenuates alcohol-, psychostimulant-,
nicotine-, and food-associated cue-induced increases in VTA
dopamine neuron activity or accumbal dopamine levels (Ege-
cioglu et al., 2013a, 2013b, 2013c; Konanur et al., 2020), sug-
gesting that GLP-1 could act by inhibiting VTA dopamine
neurons to reduce accumbal dopamine release or via direct
eﬀects on the nucleus accumbens. While such evidence points
toward the hypothesis that VTA GLP-1R signaling reduces
the motivation to work for alcohol by reducing alcohol-in-
duced increases in accumbal dopamine, it is interesting to
note that accumbal dopamine release is dependent upon the
eﬀort required to obtain the drug. For example, dopamine
release increases across trials under FR1 responding for
cocaine but when the operant requirement is elevated to FR3
or PR, the within session increase in dopamine release is
eliminated (Oliva and Wanat, 2019). This diﬀerence in
accumbal dopamine release was, however, not observed with
palatable food reward (Ko and Wanat, 2016), suggesting
that this contingency-dependent dopamine release may be
speciﬁc to the substance used. Whether this diﬀerence in
within session dopamine levels during self-administration
and PR is also observed with alcohol is unknown but the
attenuated increase in dopamine levels during PR could
potentially explain the lack of eﬀects of VTA Ex4 on PR
responding for alcohol.
Previous studies show that VTA regional diﬀerences exist
with self-stimulation of alcohol delivery to the anterior ver-
sus posterior VTA, where self-stimulation behavior is
increased when alcohol is delivered to the posterior VTA
compared to the anterior VTA (Rodd-Henricks et al., 2000).
This suggests that anterior and posterior VTA might diﬀer-
entially regulate behaviors (Ikemoto, 2007). A recent study
also showed diﬀerential eﬀects of Ex4 when delivered to the
anterior VTA versus the posterior VTA on alcohol-mediated
behaviors. GLP-1R signaling in the posterior VTA, but not
the anterior VTA, reduced home cage alcohol intake, condi-
tioned place preference for alcohol, and alcohol-induced
increases in locomotor activity (Vallof et al., 2019a). Given
that VTA cannula placements in the present study were dis-
tributed across the rostral–caudal extent of the VTA, we
sought to examine whether there are diﬀerences in the eﬀects
of Ex4 in the anterior VTA versus the posterior VTA. In con-
trast to the study by Vallof et al, we did not observe any
regional diﬀerences on the eﬀects of Ex4 on alcohol self-ad-
ministration, reacquisition, or motivation. It is possible that
the posterior VTA reported in our study is anterior to what
Vallof and colleagues considered as posterior (Bregma 5.8
vs. Bregma 6.8). It would be interesting for future studies
to examine the diﬀerential eﬀects of GLP-1R signaling in the
anterior versus posterior VTA in not only alcohol intake but
also relapse and motivation to better understand the neural
mechanisms underlying the eﬀects of GLP-1 on alcohol
intake behaviors.
It was surprising that we did not observe any eﬀects of
VTA Ex4 on reacquisition of alcohol self-administration and
motivation to work for alcohol under a PR schedule of rein-
forcement. One possible concern is the number of VTA infu-
sions. To avoid excessive intra-VTA infusions, we used a
bilateral cannula and performed unilateral infusions such
that each rat received ~5 infusions to each VTA side. We
have also previously shown that we are able to demonstrate
signiﬁcant eﬀects of Ex4 following ~5 infusions to the par-
aventricular thalamus (a brain region of similar size to uni-
lateral VTA; Ong et al., 2017). Thus, it is unlikely that the
lack of eﬀects observed with VTA Ex4 delivery on reacquisi-
tion and motivation is due to overinfusions. The lack of
eﬀects could be due to unilateral VTA Ex4 infusion, which
targets only a subpopulation of VTA GLP-1Rs. It is possible
that bilateral VTA GLP-1R agonism may be required to
emulate the eﬀects of systemic Ex4 on reacquisition and
motivation. One other possibility is that prolonged alcohol
intake can cause neuroadaptation in the mesolimbic reward
system (Gilpin and Koob, 2008). Whether VTA GLP-1Rs
are altered during this process that aﬀects sensitivity to Ex4
is yet to be characterized. Previous studies show that GLP-
1R expression in the VTA does not change after 1 or 7 days
of abstinence from drugs of abuse (Hernandez et al., 2018),
suggesting that GLP-1Rs remain intact following drug absti-
nence, but whether the same applies to chronic alcohol expo-
sure and withdrawal is to be determined. Thus, we cannot
exclude the possibility that the ineﬃcacy of VTA Ex4 during
VTA GLP-1 AND ALCOHOL SELF-ADMINISTRATION
2127
reacquisition and PR tests is due to neuroadaptive changes
in VTA GLP-1R expression.
We acknowledge some limitations in the current study. We
discuss them here and highlight future directions. First, we
measured the eﬀects of VTA Ex4 on alcohol self-administra-
tion only in male Long-Evans rats. Given the potential utility
of GLP-1 analogues as a treatment for AUDs, it is important
to determine whether females respond similarly to the eﬀects
of GLP-1 analogues on alcohol intake behaviors. There are
currently no studies that have examined and compared the
eﬀects of GLP-1 on alcohol intake in both males and females.
To our knowledge, only 1 study has used female rats and
showed that GLP-1R agonism in the nucleus accumbens
reduces alcohol intake (Abtahi et al., 2018) but other alcohol
intake behaviors including relapse were not examined. In
order to further our understanding of the mechanisms of
GLP-1 analogues on alcohol intake behaviors and its utility
as a treatment for AUDs, it is essential that future studies use
both male and female subjects in their approach to evaluate
the role of GLP-1 on alcohol intake behaviors.
Second, the rat model used here does not necessarily
model alcohol dependence. Rather, it assesses alcohol intake
behaviors in rats that voluntarily consume alcohol for its
positive reinforcing properties. Thus, whether the eﬀects
observed in this study can be extrapolated to alcohol-depen-
dent subjects are still unclear. It was previously demonstrated
that systemic administration
of
the
GLP-1R agonist,
AC3174, decreases alcohol intake in alcohol-dependent mice
(Suchankova et al., 2015) but the sites of action and whether
it also reduces other aspects of alcohol intake behaviors,
including motivation and relapse, were not examined. Thus,
future investigations into the eﬀects of GLP-1 analogues on
alcohol intake behaviors in an alcohol-dependent model are
necessary to facilitate the understanding of the function of
GLP-1 in alcohol dependence.
In conclusion, we showed for the ﬁrst time that GLP-1R
signaling in the VTA reduces alcohol self-administration but
not reacquisition of alcohol self-administration or the moti-
vation to work for alcohol. Importantly, the eﬀects on self-
administration were independent of any eﬀects on food
intake or locomotor activity. The lack of eﬀects of VTA
GLP-1R signaling on reacquisition and motivation to obtain
alcohol suggests that other mechanisms might contribute to
the eﬀects of GLP-1 on these alcohol intake behaviors. Fur-
ther studies elucidating the mechanisms of GLP-1 on alcohol
intake behaviors in both males and females, as well as in
alcohol-dependent subjects, are warranted to provide a bet-
ter understanding of the utility of GLP-1 as a potential AUD
treatment.
